,"Aft 1284":"na 1284","1309":"1309","4 April 1276":"4 april 1276","Flamstead, Hertfordshire, England":"Flamstead, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Gascony, France":"Gascogne, Frankrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","Thornby, Northamptonshire, England":"Thornby, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1255–25 May 1295":"about 1255–25 May 1295","1254–1324":"1254–1324","1255–1295":"1255–1295","–1284":"–1284","1276–1309":"1276–1309","1284–1324":"1284–1324","1235–1264":"1235–1264","26 April 1284":"26 April 1284","1264":"1264","1295":"1295","1284":"1284","25 May 1295":"25 May 1295","1290":"1290","circa 1255":"24 May 1264","1259":"1259","1324":"1324","1235":"1235","Abt 1255":"about 1255","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1254":"1254","Aft 1284":"after 1284","1309":"1309","4 April 1276":"4 April 1276","Flamstead, Hertfordshire, England":"Flamstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Gascony, France":"Gascogne, France","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","Thornby, Northamptonshire, England":"Thornby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tosny","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jean Pierre.","Americanized form of any of various surnames ultimately derived from the Latin personal name <i>Antonius</i> (see   Anthony  ), for example Greek   Antoniou   and Italian   Toni  .","French: from the personal name <i>Tony</i>, a pet form of <i>Antonin</i> (from Latin <i>Antoninus</i>, a derivative of <i>Antonius</i>; see   Anthony  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Anthony","meanings":["English and West Indian (mainly Antigua and Barbuda, Saint Lucia, and Trinidad and Tobago, also Dutch Caribbean): from the personal name <i>Anthony</i>, Latin <i>Antonius</i>, which, with its variants and cognates, is one of the commonest personal names in Europe. Spellings with <i>-h-</i>, which first appear in English in the 16th century and in French (as <i>Anthoine</i>) at about the same time, are due to the erroneous belief that the name derives from Greek <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. The popularity of the personal name in Christendom is largely due to the cult of the Egyptian hermit Saint Anthony (  AD  251–356), who in his old age gathered a community of hermits around him, and for that reason is regarded by some as the founder of monasticism. It was further increased by the fame of Saint Anthony of Padua (1195–1231), who long enjoyed a great popular cult and who is believed to help people find lost things. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates and derivatives (patronymics) from other languages, for example Greek patronymic   Antoniades  , Italian   Antoni  , Polish   Antoniewicz  , Croatian and Serbian <b>Antonović</b> (see   Antonovich  ) and <b>Antunović</b>; see also below. The name <i>Anthony</i> is also found among Christians in southern India, but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Antony  .","German, Flemish, and French (mainly Alsace): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Antonius</i>, from its genitive form <i>Antoni(i)</i>. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the German, Dutch, French, and Slovak cognates   Antoni   1 and   Antony   2.","History: John Anthony of Hampstead, Middlesex, England (now part of north London) migrated to Boston, MA, in 1634. By 1640 he had moved to Providence, RI, where his descendants are still established."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":35,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph de Tosny was born about 1255, in Flamstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger de Tosny, was 21 and his mother, Alice de Bohun, was 21. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mary. He died on 25 May 1295, in Gascogne, F